**NoUI Platform**

Dynamic Workspace

User Experience Architecture

*How AI Presents the Right Work Surface at the Right Time*

DERP Proof of Concept

February 2026

*DRAFT --- Working Architecture Document*

**1. The Core Insight: Work Comes to the Worker**

Traditional pension administration systems are built around screens.
Staff navigate through menus, hunt for the right form, pull up multiple
windows, and mentally assemble the context they need. NoUI inverts this
entirely. The system understands what work needs to be done, assembles
the exact information and tools needed for that specific task, and
presents it as a single, cohesive workspace. The worker never navigates.
The work arrives ready.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Design Philosophy**                                                 |
|                                                                       |
| *The best interface is the one you never have to think about. NoUI    |
| does not present a pension administration system. It presents the     |
| next thing you need to do, with everything you need to do it, and     |
| nothing you don't.*                                                   |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

This document defines how the Dynamic Workspace layer delivers on that
promise --- from the workflow queue that drives the worker's day,
through the micro-interaction patterns that collect and validate data,
to the learning loops that make the system progressively smarter about
how it routes and presents work.

**2. The Work Queue: The Heartbeat of the System**

When a staff member opens NoUI, they do not see a dashboard of member
records or a menu of system functions. They see their work queue --- a
prioritized, filterable list of tasks waiting for their attention. This
is the primary entry point for all interaction.

**2.1 Queue as Primary Interface**

The work queue is not a sidebar or secondary view. It is the home
screen. Every piece of work in the system --- a retirement application
to process, a benefit calculation to verify, a DRO to apply, a data
quality finding to review --- exists as a work item in somebody's queue.
Work items arrive through defined channels: a member submits a
retirement application, a supervisor routes a case for review, the data
quality engine surfaces a finding, or the process orchestrator advances
a multi-stage workflow to the next step.

Each work item in the queue shows just enough to orient the worker
before they open it: the member's name and ID, the task type, the tier
(color-coded), how long it has been waiting, any flags (DRO present,
data quality issue, early retirement penalty), and its priority. The
worker taps a work item, and the full workspace assembles.

**2.2 Intelligent Prioritization**

The queue is not a simple FIFO list. The system applies intelligent
ordering based on multiple factors: regulatory deadlines (statutory
processing windows), member impact (a retiring member waiting for their
first check takes precedence over a routine verification), case
complexity (simple cases that can be completed quickly are surfaced to
prevent backlog accumulation), dependency chains (if case B depends on
case A's completion, case A is promoted), and staff workload balancing
(distributing complex cases evenly across the team).

In Phase 1 (Transparent), all prioritization logic is visible. Workers
can see why a particular item is at the top of their queue and can
manually reorder if they disagree. Over time, the system learns which
prioritization signals correlate with efficient processing and adjusts
its recommendations accordingly.

**2.3 Queue Filtering and Views**

Workers can slice their queue by task type (retirement applications,
verifications, DRO processing), by tier (show only Tier 3 cases), by
status (waiting for documents, ready to calculate, pending supervisor
review), by age (items older than five business days), or by flag (all
cases with data quality findings). Supervisors see their team's
aggregate queue with the same filters plus assignment controls. The
system remembers each worker's preferred view and restores it on login.

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Queue          **What It Shows**        **Why It Matters**
  Element**                                 
  ---------------- ------------------------ ------------------------------
  Member Identity  Name, ID, tier badge     Instant recognition and tier
                   (color-coded)            context

  Task Type        Retirement Application,  Worker knows what kind of work
                   DRO Review, etc.         this is

  Wait Time        Time since item entered  Urgency signal, prevents items
                   queue                    aging out

  Flags            DRO, early penalty, data Complexity preview before
                   quality, purchased svc   opening

  Priority         Calculated rank with     Transparent ordering workers
  Indicator        visible reasoning        can trust

  Stage            Application Review,      Where in the process this item
                   Calculation, Final       sits
                   Approval                 

  Quick Actions    Claim, Reassign, Flag    Common actions without opening
                   for Supervisor           full workspace
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

**3. Workspace Assembly: Context-Driven Composition**

When a worker selects a work item from their queue, the system assembles
a workspace. This is not loading a screen. It is a dynamic composition
where the system evaluates everything it knows about this member, this
task, and this stage of the process, and constructs the exact set of
components the worker needs.

**3.1 The Composition Pipeline**

Workspace assembly follows the established three-tier composition model.
Tier 1 (Deterministic) uses the process configuration to define the base
workspace: a retirement application at the calculation stage always
includes the member banner, employment timeline, salary table, and
benefit calculation panel. Tier 2 (Rule-Based) evaluates situational
factors and adjusts: if the member has a DRO, the DRO impact panel
appears; if they are eligible for leave payout, the leave payout
calculator is added; if they have purchased service, a prominent callout
highlights that purchased service is excluded from Rule of 75/85
eligibility. Tier 3 (AI Augmentation) handles genuinely novel situations
--- combinations of factors that the rule-based system has not
encountered before.

The critical point: Tier 1 and Tier 2 together handle the vast majority
of cases. Tier 3 is invoked rarely. The workspace is fully functional
without any AI service, per the established degradation hierarchy. When
AI does contribute, it affects layout and emphasis, never the data
displayed.

**3.2 Progressive Disclosure Within the Workspace**

Once assembled, the workspace itself follows a principle of progressive
disclosure. Not every component is displayed at full depth
simultaneously. The workspace opens with the most critical information
for the current stage expanded and ready for interaction, while
secondary components are present but collapsed to a summary line. The
worker can expand any component with a single tap, but the system's
judgment about what matters most guides the initial view.

For example, when processing Robert Martinez's retirement (Case 1), the
workspace at the calculation stage opens with the benefit calculation
panel fully expanded, showing the formula, every input, and the result.
The salary table shows a summary line ("AMS: \$8,542.31/mo --- highest
36 consecutive months ending March 2026") that expands to the full
monthly breakdown on tap. The employment timeline shows the total (28
years, 9 months) with the full chronology available on expansion. The
DRO panel is absent because Robert has no DRO. The leave payout section
is expanded because it directly impacts the AMS.

**3.3 Completeness Indicators**

A distinctive feature: every summarized or filtered view includes a
completeness indicator. The salary table summary says "Showing 3 of 28
years --- highest average calculation period." The employment timeline
says "4 employment records --- all shown." The service credit summary
says "28.75 years earned service --- no purchased service." Workers
always know what they are seeing relative to the whole picture. Nothing
is hidden; some things are simply prioritized.

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Relevance Engine Principle**                                        |
|                                                                       |
| *Show everything, prioritize what matters. Default to inclusion, not  |
| exclusion. The workspace never hides data that a competent analyst    |
| might want to see. It foregrounds what the current task requires and  |
| backgrounds the rest --- but the rest is always one tap away.*        |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**4. Micro-Interaction Patterns: Small Bites, Not Wizards**

Traditional pension systems present massive forms. A retirement
application screen might have 40 fields across multiple tabs, mixing
data entry, validation feedback, and calculation results in a single
overwhelming view. NoUI takes a fundamentally different approach.

**4.1 Focused Data Collection Steps**

Instead of one monolithic form, the system presents small, focused
interaction steps. Each step collects or confirms a specific, coherent
set of data. A retirement application might flow through steps like:
confirm retirement date and type, verify employment history is complete,
confirm salary data and AMS window, review eligibility determination,
review benefit calculation, select payment option and beneficiary, and
final certification. Each step shows only the fields relevant to that
step, with contextual guidance explaining what the system needs and why.

This is not a traditional wizard with a linear Back/Next flow. The
process orchestrator defines the steps and their dependencies, but the
worker can navigate non-linearly when the dependencies allow it. If the
salary data is already verified, the worker can jump directly to the
eligibility determination. The system tracks which steps are complete,
which are in progress, and which are blocked by dependencies --- and
displays this as a lightweight progress indicator at the top of the
workspace.

**4.2 Inline Validation with Contextual Feedback**

Each field validates as the worker interacts with it, not when they
submit a form. But the validation goes beyond simple format checking.
The system provides contextual, intelligent feedback that helps the
worker understand the implications of the data.

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Interaction**   **Traditional System**  **NoUI Approach**
  ----------------- ----------------------- -------------------------------
  Retirement date   Date picker, error if   Date picker that immediately
  entry             invalid                 shows: "Age at retirement: 63.
                                            Service: 28y 9m. Meets Rule of
                                            75 (91.75). No reduction."

  Payment option    Dropdown list of codes  Side-by-side comparison showing
  selection                                 monthly amount for each option
                                            with the member's actual
                                            numbers, spouse age factored in

  Salary            Scrollable table of 28  AMS window highlighted with
  confirmation      years                   callout: "Leave payout of
                                            \$52,000 boosted final month.
                                            AMS impact: +\$214.32/mo"

  Beneficiary       Name/DOB/relationship   Pre-populated from existing
  designation       fields                  records, with spousal consent
                                            requirement flagged if married
                                            and selecting less than 50% J&S
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------

**4.3 Contextual Intelligence Within Steps**

Each step is context-aware. When the worker is on the payment option
selection step for Robert Martinez (Case 1), the system knows Robert is
married to Elena (age 59), knows he is selecting 75% J&S, and can
immediately show both the member's reduced benefit and the survivor
benefit amount. If the worker changes the selection to Maximum (single
life), the system notes the spousal consent requirement: "Elena Martinez
must sign spousal consent waiver for this option." The system never
blocks the selection --- it informs and flags.

For Jennifer Kim (Case 2), the scenario modeler is embedded directly in
the eligibility step. When the system shows that Jennifer does not meet
Rule of 75 and faces a 60% reduction, it immediately presents the key
insight: "Waiting 2 more years to age 57 meets Rule of 75 --- no
reduction. Monthly benefit increases from approximately \$1,400 to
approximately \$4,200." This is not a separate analysis tool the worker
must navigate to; it is part of the natural flow of processing the case.
The exact figures come from the deterministic rules engine; the
presentation decision comes from the composition system.

**4.4 Save and Resume**

Every interaction automatically saves state. If a worker is midway
through processing a retirement application and gets pulled away --- a
phone call, a supervisor question, end of shift --- they can close the
workspace entirely. When they return to the work item in their queue,
the workspace reassembles exactly where they left off, with every field
they've touched preserved, every step's completion state intact, and a
subtle indicator showing what they were last working on.

**5. Intelligent Routing: Learning How Work Flows**

The Process Orchestrator defines the formal stages and rules for how
cases move through the system. But within those formal constraints,
there is significant room for intelligence about how work actually gets
routed and sequenced. This is where AI-driven operational learning
applies --- in accordance with ADR-003: AI learns orchestration, not
rules.

**5.1 What the System Learns**

By observing how work flows through the system, NoUI builds an
increasingly refined model of operational patterns. This includes
processing time patterns (Tier 1 retirements with leave payouts take 40%
longer than without --- the system learns to allocate more time and not
penalize workers in productivity metrics), common navigation paths (most
analysts reviewing a DRO case access the employment timeline before the
DRO panel to understand the marital period in context --- the system
learns to position these adjacently), exception patterns (cases routed
back from supervisor review most commonly fail on the same three
verification points --- the system learns to emphasize those points
during the initial processing step), and expertise matching (certain
analysts process Tier 3 cases more efficiently because they are more
familiar with the 60-month AMS window --- the system learns to route
accordingly when workload permits).

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **ADR-003 Boundary**                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| *AI learns from transaction history how work gets done --- task       |
| patterns, data access sequences, workflow flows. AI does not derive   |
| business rules from transaction patterns. Rules come from governing   |
| documents only. The insights described here inform routing and        |
| presentation. They never inform eligibility, calculation, or          |
| determination.*                                                       |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**5.2 Progressive Routing Refinement**

Routing intelligence develops through three phases. In the initial phase
(rule-based only), the Process Orchestrator routes based on configured
rules: task type determines the processing queue, supervisors assign
from their team queue, escalation follows defined thresholds (for
example, any benefit exceeding a configured dollar amount requires
senior review). In the observation phase, the system begins tracking
patterns passively. It records which analysts handle which case types,
how long processing takes by case characteristics, where cases stall or
get returned, and what data workers access in what order. All
observations are logged and available for human review but do not yet
influence routing. In the recommendation phase, the system begins making
routing suggestions: recommending case assignments based on observed
expertise and current workload, suggesting workspace layouts based on
observed access patterns, flagging cases likely to need escalation based
on historical pattern matching, and proposing process refinements based
on exception analysis. All suggestions are presented transparently and
require human acceptance.

**5.3 How Routing Feels to the Worker**

From the worker's perspective, intelligent routing manifests as the
system getting progressively better at putting the right work in front
of them. In the early weeks, their queue is ordered by simple rules
(oldest first within priority tiers). Over months, the queue starts to
feel curated: the cases that match their expertise and current cognitive
state appear at natural moments, complex cases arrive when they have
uninterrupted time, simple cases cluster when they are between meetings.

Workers never feel managed by the system. They can always manually
reorder their queue, claim cases from the team pool, or reassign items.
The system's intelligence is advisory, not directive. If a worker
consistently overrides the system's routing for a particular case type,
the system learns that preference rather than fighting it.

**6. Visual Design Language**

The workspace must feel modern and clean while communicating complex
pension information with clarity. The design language prioritizes
readability, clear hierarchy, and purposeful use of color.

**6.1 Layout Principles**

The workspace uses a single-column primary layout with a persistent
member banner at top. There is no sidebar navigation --- the queue is
the navigation. Content flows vertically in order of relevance.
Components are visually separated by subtle cards with consistent
padding, light borders, and generous whitespace. The overall aesthetic
is closer to a well-designed financial dashboard than a government form.
Typography uses a clear hierarchy: component titles at one weight,
labels at another, data values prominent and easily scannable.

**6.2 Color as Information**

Color carries meaning throughout the interface, not decoration. Tier
identification uses a consistent color-coding system (such as blue for
Tier 1, amber for Tier 2, green for Tier 3) that appears in the member
banner, the queue cards, and anywhere tier-specific provisions apply.
Alert colors follow standard conventions: red for issues requiring
immediate attention (critical data quality findings, processing deadline
approaching), amber for cautions (early retirement penalty applies,
spousal consent required), and informational blue for contextual notes.
The AMS calculation window is highlighted within the salary table so the
worker can instantly see which months contribute to the benefit.
Calculation panels use subtle background shading to visually distinguish
inputs, formulas, and results.

**6.3 Animation and Transitions**

Transitions are purposeful and brief. When a workspace assembles,
components appear in a quick staggered sequence (not simultaneously) so
the worker's eye follows the composition and understands the structure.
When a component expands from summary to detail, the transition is
smooth and fast (under 200ms) --- no jarring content shifts. When
validation feedback appears, it fades in adjacent to the relevant field
rather than popping up in a modal. Progress indicators use subtle
animated fills rather than static bars. The overall feel should be
responsive and alive without being distracting.

**6.4 Mobile Responsiveness**

While the primary use case is desktop workstations, the workspace must
function on tablets (for field visits or offsite processing) and degrade
gracefully on phones (for supervisors reviewing and approving on the
go). The component-based architecture naturally supports responsive
layouts: cards stack vertically on narrow screens, tables become
scrollable or transform to card-based layouts, and the member banner
collapses to essential information with an expand option.

**7. The Four Demo Cases as UX Proof Points**

Each demonstration case showcases specific UX capabilities. Here is how
the workspace behaves differently for each, illustrating the composition
system's intelligence.

**7.1 Case 1: Robert Martinez --- Workspace Highlights Leave Payout
Impact**

When the worker opens Robert's retirement case, the workspace assembles
with the leave payout calculator prominently positioned adjacent to the
salary table. The AMS window highlight in the salary table extends to
show the final month where the \$52,000 leave payout is added, with a
visual callout showing the before-and-after AMS effect. The eligibility
section shows a clean green indicator: Rule of 75 satisfied (91.75). The
payment options comparison is expanded because Robert has selected 75%
J&S, and the system shows both the member and survivor benefit with
Elena's age factored in. The workspace does not show a DRO panel,
purchased service callout, or early retirement reduction calculator ---
none of these apply.

**7.2 Case 2: Jennifer Kim --- Workspace Highlights the Dramatic
Penalty**

Jennifer's workspace opens with a prominent amber alert: "Early
retirement reduction applies --- 60% reduction from maximum benefit."
The scenario modeler is embedded directly in the calculation panel,
pre-loaded with the comparison: current retirement date versus two years
from now. The visual impact is dramatic: a side-by-side showing the
monthly benefit nearly tripling if Jennifer waits. The purchased service
section includes a clear callout: "3 years purchased service ---
included in benefit calculation, excluded from Rule of 75 eligibility."
This is the single most important distinction the system needs to
communicate, and the workspace makes it unmissable.

**7.3 Case 3: David Washington --- Workspace Adapts for Tier 3
Provisions**

David's workspace demonstrates tier-aware composition. The salary table
is configured for the 60-month AMS window (not 36), and the highlight is
visually distinct to signal the different calculation period. The
eligibility section shows Rule of 85 (not Rule of 75), with the current
score (76.58) and the gap clearly displayed. The early retirement
reduction is 12% (two years under 65), much less dramatic than
Jennifer's case, and the workspace presents it proportionally --- as a
notable but manageable factor, not a crisis.

**7.4 Case 4: Robert Martinez with DRO --- Workspace Adds DRO Layer**

This case demonstrates incremental composition. The workspace starts
identical to Case 1, then adds the DRO impact panel. The DRO panel shows
the marital period on the employment timeline (visually overlaid), the
marital fraction calculation (18.25/28.75 = 63.48%), and the split
amounts. The payment options comparison now shows three columns: member
portion, alternate payee portion, and total. The workspace handles the
complexity of DRO interaction with payment options by presenting it as a
natural extension of the existing calculation, not as a separate
workflow.

**8. Implementation Plan for the POC**

This UX architecture breaks down into concrete implementation areas. The
following plan sequences the work for the DERP proof of concept,
focusing on what demonstrates the concept most effectively with limited
resources.

**8.1 Phase A: Queue and Shell**

Build the application shell with the work queue as the primary view.
This includes the queue data model (work items with type, member
reference, stage, priority, flags, timestamps, and assignment), the
queue API (list, filter, claim, reassign, update status), the queue UI
(filterable list with tier color-coding, flag badges, wait-time display,
and priority indicators), and the workspace shell (member banner,
progress indicator, component container). For the POC, the queue is
pre-populated with the four demo cases plus a set of additional
synthetic work items to demonstrate filtering and prioritization. The
routing is rule-based only (Phase 1 of the routing intelligence).

**8.2 Phase B: Component Library**

Build the individual workspace components as self-contained, composable
units. Each component receives its data through a consistent props
interface from the workspace composition engine: the member banner
(persistent header with tier badge, status, and key identifiers), the
employment timeline (visual chronology with DRO overlay capability), the
salary table (with configurable AMS window highlighting for 36-month or
60-month windows), the benefit calculation panel (full formula display
with expandable derivation steps), the payment options comparison
(side-by-side cards with actual calculated amounts), the scenario
modeler (interactive date comparison with live recalculation), the DRO
impact panel (marital fraction visualization and split amounts), and the
supporting calculators (leave payout, early retirement reduction, IPR).

**8.3 Phase C: Composition Engine**

Wire the composition engine to the workspace shell. This is where the
Tier 1 and Tier 2 composition logic assembles the correct components for
each case. The composition engine receives the member context (tier,
status, flags), the process context (type, current stage), and the
situational context (DRO present, purchased service, leave payout
eligible) and returns a workspace definition: which components to
include, their initial expanded or collapsed state, their ordering, and
any contextual parameters (such as the AMS window size for the salary
table). The four demo cases serve as the integration test suite: each
must produce the correct workspace composition with the correct
components in the correct states.

**8.4 Phase D: Micro-Interaction Polish**

Refine the interaction patterns within each component. This includes
inline validation with contextual feedback (not just format checking but
domain-aware responses), progressive disclosure (expand/collapse with
completeness indicators), the focused data collection flow for the
retirement application process (small steps with non-linear navigation),
auto-save with resume capability, and transitions (staggered component
entry, smooth expand/collapse, contextual fade-in for validation
feedback).

**8.5 Phase E: Operational Intelligence (Post-POC Foundation)**

For the POC, operational intelligence is demonstrated through the
transaction analysis dashboard showing patterns discovered in the
synthetic data. The actual routing refinement and workspace optimization
based on learned patterns is a post-POC capability. However, the POC
architecture should include the observation hooks (logging which
components workers interact with, in what order, for how long) so the
learning system has data to work with once deployed.

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Phase**            **Core Deliverable**       **Demo Impact**
  -------------------- -------------------------- -----------------------------
  A: Queue and Shell   Work queue as primary UI,  \"Work comes to the worker,
                       workspace container        not the other way around\"

  B: Component Library All workspace components   \"The system shows exactly
                       as composable units        what you need for each case\"

  C: Composition       Tier 1+2 workspace         \"The workspace adapts
  Engine               assembly                   automatically based on the
                                                  member and the task\"

  D:                   Inline validation,         \"It feels modern,
  Micro-Interactions   progressive disclosure,    responsive, and intelligent\"
                       save/resume                

  E: Intelligence      Observation logging,       \"It learns how your team
  Hooks                transaction analysis       works and gets smarter over
                       dashboard                  time\"
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

**9. What This Is Not**

It is worth being explicit about what the NoUI workspace does not do, to
set expectations correctly for stakeholders reviewing this document.

It is not a chatbot. Workers do not type natural language queries to get
pension information. They interact with structured components that
present deterministic data. AI operates behind the scenes in composition
and routing, not as a conversational interface.

It is not a self-service portal. This architecture describes the
staff-facing workspace for pension administrators. Member self-service
(where retirees or active members check their accounts) is a separate
concern not addressed in the POC.

It is not a replacement for human judgment. The system presents
information, performs deterministic calculations, and suggests routing.
Every determination, approval, and certification requires a human. The
POC operates exclusively in Phase 1 (Transparent), where every output is
presented for human verification.

It is not a reporting tool. While the workspace includes analytical
components (scenario modeler, data quality dashboard), it is not
designed for ad hoc reporting or data exports. Reporting is a separate
capability that sits alongside the workspace, not within it.

